>
  <section class="cover">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow cover-eyebrow">05 · Adoption · Trust · Leadership</p>
      <h1>What the<br />organisation<br /><em>experiences,</em> sees,<br />and decides.</h1>
      <p class="cover-sub">
        How a transforming organisation adopts Interphase — the trust
        architecture, what leadership actually sees, why non-participation is
        signal, and how ROI is measured without mandate.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The adoption challenge</p>
        <h2>Adoption as <em>by-product,</em> not goal</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Every platform that depends on honest human input faces the same foundational question: why would someone use this truthfully? For Interphase, the answer is not incentive design or mandate — it is structural trust.</p>
          <p>The only way to get genuine signal about what is actually happening in an organisation during transformation is to create a space where people feel genuinely safe to be honest. The moment anyone suspects that their reflection could be traced back to them — used in a performance review, seen by their manager, weaponised in a restructuring — the data collapses into performance.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"We start with radical transparency, and let the quality of the experience prove the case. Trustworthiness is not a tactical tool — it is the foundation. Adoption is a by-product of genuine trust, not of mandate or persuasion."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Interphase — Adoption Philosophy</div>
          </div>

          <p>This means Interphase's adoption model is the inverse of most enterprise software: it does not seek maximum participation through incentives, gamification, or top-down mandate. It seeks honest participation through structural guarantees. A smaller number of genuinely honest reflections produces better signal than a large number of performed ones.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The trust architecture</p>
        <h2>Structural guarantees,<br /><em>not policy promises</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>The privacy model cannot be a legal disclaimer or a HR communications message. It must be a structural reality — something that is architecturally true, not just contractually promised.</p>

          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>Individual data sovereignty</h4><p>Every reflection belongs entirely to the individual who created it. No manager, HR professional, or Interphase employee can access individual content. Enforced at the database layer with Row Level Security — not just through policy.</p></div>
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>Participation thresholds</h4><p>Aggregate signal is only generated above a configured participation threshold — minimum five contributors per signal point. Below that, no signal is surfaced. Individual attribution is structurally impossible even in small teams.</p></div>
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>Transparent mechanics</h4><p>Every employee can see exactly what data is generated, at what level of aggregation, and who can see what. The transparency is not about showing the data — it is about showing the system.</p></div>
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>Right to exit</h4><p>Participation is always voluntary. Opting out has no consequence. Crucially, non-participation itself is understood as signal, not as gap. No one is nudged or incentivised.</p></div>
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>No performance cross-contamination</h4><p>Interphase data is structurally separated from HR systems, performance management, and any tool that carries performance consequences. The connection cannot be made — the data pipelines do not exist.</p></div>
            <div class="tc-cell"><h4>Consent architecture</h4><p>Data is used only for what was consented to. Interphase cannot repurpose reflection data for commercial analytics or AI training without explicit, granular consent. The ethical commitment is the commercial moat.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The adoption journey</p>
        <h2>How it enters<br /><em>and takes root</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">01</div>
              <div class="row-label">Entry trigger<strong>A defined event</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>M&amp;A integration, ESG mandate, leadership succession, or digital rollout</h4>
                <p>Interphase is introduced in the context of a named transformation — not as a general HR tool, but as infrastructure for a specific, high-stakes change. Leadership adopts because the transformation is real, the risk is known, and traditional consulting does not scale to their context.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">02</div>
              <div class="row-label">Consent<strong>Transparent launch</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Leadership communicates the system clearly before inviting participation</h4>
                <p>What Interphase is. What it captures. What it does not capture. Who can see what, at what level of aggregation. The launch communication is not a sales pitch — it is a structural explanation. People join because they understand what they are joining.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">03</div>
              <div class="row-label">Early phase<strong>Experience builds trust</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>The first few reflections prove the promise</h4>
                <p>The experience of using the platform — the quality of the questions, the absence of surveillance cues, the feeling of genuine privacy — does the work that no communication can. Trust is not built by promises; it is built by experience.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">04</div>
              <div class="row-label">Momentum<strong>Intrinsic motivation</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>People return because reflection is valuable to them personally</h4>
                <p>The SDT flywheel activates: low-effort experience → growing competence as a reflector → increased autonomy and relational safety → intrinsic motivation to return → richer reflections. The person is no longer using Interphase because the organisation deployed it.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Non-participation as signal</p>
        <h2>Absence is not a gap.<br /><em>It is data.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="callout">
            <h3>The participation intelligence reframe</h3>
            <h2>Non-participation is itself <em>meaningful information.</em></h2>
            <p>Traditional enterprise software treats low adoption as a product failure to be corrected through nudges, reminders, and gamification. Interphase treats it differently.</p>
            <p>A function that chooses not to participate is telling you something — about trust levels, about perceived safety, about their relationship with leadership, or about their experience of the transformation itself. That signal is as valuable as any reflection content. The Chaperone reads non-participation patterns with the same interpretive lens as participation data.</p>
            <p>This reframe resolves the participation bias objection entirely: Interphase does not have a participation bias problem, because it has named non-participation as a feature of its signal architecture — not a flaw in its product design.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">What leadership sees</p>
        <h2>Interpreted guidance,<br /><em>not raw data</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>Leadership never sees individual reflections. They do not see aggregate scores on a dashboard. What they see is the Chaperone's interpreted guidance — professional judgment informed by signal that was not previously available to any practitioner.</p>

          <div class="mock">
            <div class="mock-head">Chaperone guidance — illustrative · month 3 of M&amp;A integration</div>
            <div class="mock-grid">
              <div class="mock-cell">
                <div class="mc-n"><em>74</em>%</div>
                <div class="mc-l">Participation — finance & ops</div>
              </div>
              <div class="mock-cell">
                <div class="mc-n"><em>41</em>%</div>
                <div class="mc-l">Participation — commercial</div>
              </div>
              <div class="mock-cell">
                <div class="mc-n"><em>↑</em>3</div>
                <div class="mc-l">Avg. dimensions engaged vs week 1</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="mock-signal">
              <div class="mock-signal-l">Chaperone interpretation</div>
              <p>"Finance and Ops are processing the integration actively — reflective depth is increasing and the data shows emerging capacity around structural navigation. The commercial team's low participation is significant: this correlates with two themes surfaced in my session last week — uncertainty about role definition and low perceived safety to express concerns upward. Recommend a targeted session with commercial leads before the next integration milestone."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="mock-foot">Illustrative — no individual attribution. Participation data aggregated above threshold.</div>
