  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Return on investment</p>
        <h2>What gets measured,<br /><em>what gets moved</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>The ROI from Interphase is not speculative. It operates at the intersection of three documented cost centres where transformations generate their most expensive failures.</p>

          <div class="tiles">
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Voluntary turnover</h4>
              <div class="tech">50–200% of annual salary</div>
              <p>Replacement cost per leaver. Interphase's early signal identifies disengagement before it becomes departure.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Resistance reduction</h4>
              <div class="tech">72% of failures: resistance gaps</div>
              <p>Resistance is an information and safety problem. Interphase gives people a safe place to process friction and leaders early signal of where it concentrates.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Timeline compression</h4>
              <div class="tech">5.3× more likely to succeed</div>
              <p>Organisations that complete their Interphase reach genuine transformation faster — capacity was built before the visible change, not during it.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Consulting displacement</h4>
              <div class="tech">10–50× cost efficiency</div>
              <p>500-person org at €12/seat/month = €72k ARR. McKinsey for the same transformation: €500k–2M. Replaces the data layer, not the strategic relationship.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"Companies that invest in culture change are 5.3× more likely to achieve transformation success than those that invest in technology alone."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">McKinsey & BCG Research, 2024</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Common objections</p>
        <h2>Questions from<br /><em>the C-suite</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="qa">
            <div class="qa-row">
              <div class="qa-q">Won't people just say what they think we want to hear?</div>
              <div class="qa-a">Only if they believe someone is listening who has power over them. The structural privacy guarantee — enforced at the database layer, not through policy — removes the social calculus from the reflection. The Question Engine's non-evaluative discipline further reduces performance pressure: there is no right answer to pursue. People quickly discover that the space is genuinely private and genuinely non-judgmental. The quality of data that emerges is categorically different from survey data.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="qa-row">
              <div class="qa-q">What if adoption is low?</div>
              <div class="qa-a">Low adoption is managed as signal, not as failure. The Chaperone reads non-participation patterns as meaningful information about the organisation's relationship with the transformation. Interphase does not nudge, remind, or incentivise — because coerced reflection produces worthless data. A platform with 40% honest participation generates better signal than one with 90% performative participation.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="qa-row">
              <div class="qa-q">How is this different from our current engagement survey?</div>
              <div class="qa-a">Engagement surveys measure sentiment at a moment in time. They ask people to evaluate their experience publicly. They produce data that is episodic, static, and subject to social desirability bias. Interphase generates continuous, longitudinal, privately-authored reflection that builds capacity rather than measuring it. The output is not a score — it is an organisational learning trajectory.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="qa-row">
              <div class="qa-q">How do we know this is working?</div>
              <div class="qa-a">Three concurrent outcome signals: platform participation trends (are people returning voluntarily, reflecting intrinsic motivation), reflective depth metrics (are individuals engaging more dimensions over time, reflecting capacity growth), and transformation outcomes (burnout rates, voluntary turnover, resistance indicators, transformation timeline adherence). The Chaperone's interpreted guidance ties platform signal to these measurable business outcomes.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
